Ringgit Hits 14-Year High on Rate-Rise Prospects; Bonds Advance

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-07-27T08:29:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-27/ringgit-hits-14-year-high-on-rate-rise-prospects-bonds-advance.html
Malaysia ’s ringgit rose to its
strongest level in almost 14 years on speculation interest rates
will be increased to contain inflation, helping spur inflows.  The currency was set for its biggest two-day gain this
month versus the dollar, which fell against four of  Southeast
Asia ’s most-used currencies, as U.S. lawmakers failed to agree
on plans to raise the nation’s debt limit. Interest-rate swaps
gained after  Bank Negara  Malaysia Governor Zeti Akhtar Aziz said
July 25 that taming inflation is “critical,” a week after she
described borrowing costs as being “quite low.” Bonds rose
before a government debt auction.  “This is a broad dollar weakness trend coupled with
renewed rate-hike optimism in  Asia ,” said Choong Yin Pheng,
manager for economic and bond research at Hong Leong Bank Bhd.
in Kuala Lumpur. “We could see more recycling of funds into
non-dollar assets. It’s still a volatile market.”  The ringgit strengthened 0.5 percent to 2.9400 per dollar
as of 4:25 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The currency’s 1.1 percent gain in two days is the
most since June 30. It earlier touched 2.9335, the strongest
level since September 1997.  The Dollar Index gained 0.1 percent, after an almost 1
percent loss in the previous two days. President  Barack Obama 
threatened a veto of House Speaker John Boehner’s two-step plan
to raise the $14.3 trillion debt ceiling and cut $3 trillion in
expenditure. The Office of Management and Budget said it
“strongly opposes” the measure, on which the Republican-
controlled House is set to vote before an Aug. 2 deadline.  Rate Swap  The cost of fixing  interest rates  for one year in Malaysia
rose 4.5 basis points, or 0.045 percentage point, to a three-
week high of 3.47 percent.  Bank Negara kept its overnight rate at 3 percent on July 7,
after lifting it once in 2011 and three times in 2010. Policy
makers next meet on Sept. 8 to review borrowing costs. Benchmark
rates are a maximum 0.25 percent in the U.S. and  Japan .  Global funds boosted their holdings of Malaysian local-
currency debt to a record 181.5 billion ringgit ($61.8 billion)
in May, up 93 percent from a year earlier, central bank data
show. The holdings include 87.9 billion ringgit of  government
bonds . The June data are due later this month.  “There is good offshore support for local assets given the
appreciation in the ringgit,” said Karen Wan, senior manager
for credit research in  Kuala Lumpur  at Ambank Bhd. “Economic
fundamentals in the region are still strong.”  Ten-year notes gained, pushing yields to a one-week low, on
optimism currency appreciation will lure more foreign buyers at
a government debt auction tomorrow.  The yield on the 4.16 percent note due July 2021 dropped
three basis points to 3.87 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia.
The price increased 0.20, or 2 ringgit per 1,000 ringgit face
amount, to 102.35.  The treasury will auction 4 billion ringgit of April 2021
Shariah-compliant notes tomorrow, according to its sale calendar.
It will also sell 2.5 billion ringgit of the same bonds in a
direct sale to investors.  To contact the reporter on this story:
